**Bottom line:** Redis Streams wins decisively. Kafka's technical advantages (higher throughput, automatic rebalancing, partition scaling, ecosystem) are real, but they're irrelevant at our current scale and actively harmful given the team constraints — a 6-person team with zero Kafka experience and no dedicated infra engineer would spend months fighting operational complexity before seeing any benefit. Redis Streams delivers value in under a week using infrastructure already deployed, monitored, and understood.

The ADR covers all seven properties you specified (throughput, ordering, retention, consumer groups, exactly-once, operational complexity, team constraints) and explicitly addresses why exactly-once is a consumer-side problem regardless of broker choice.
